===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[path]].
# An unspecified distance.
#: '''1912''' Jack Judge and Henry "Harry" James Williams, a marching and music hall song, ''It`s a Long Way to Tipperary'', popularized esp. by British troops in World War One:
#:* It`s a long '''way''' to Tipperary, / it`s a long '''way''' to go.
# A method of doing something.
# The means to navigate a path.
# Possiblility (usually in the phrases 'any way' and 'no way').
# {{context|paganism}} A tradition within the modern [[pagan]] faith of [[Heathenry]], dedication to a specific deity or craft, Way of [[wyrd]], Way of [[runes]], Way of [[Thor]] etc.
# {{context|nautical}} '''ways''' the sloping structures on which ships are built and launched

====Quotations====
* (''means to navigate a path'') "Do you know the way to San Jose?" <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[w:Do You Know the Way to San Jose|song title]] and lyric, [[w:Burt Bacharach|Bacharach]] and [[w:Hal David|David]]]
